ulture. He was also a rebel who accused the Jewish leadership of Salonica of being corrupt, abusive, and fanatical; that leadership, in turn, excommunicated him from the Jewish community. The experience of excommunication pervades Sa'adi's memoir, which documents a world that its author was himself actively involved in changing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aJewish journalistsxBiographyxGreecexThessalonikē. 0aJewish publishersxBiographyxGreecexThessalonikē. 0aSephardimxHistoryx19th centuryxGreecexThessalonikē. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aJerusalmi, Isaac1 aRodrigue, Aron, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStein, Sarah Abrevaya, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804781770zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804781770423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804781770.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles